{"timestamp": "2025-12-16 15:06:28.578514", "event": "llm_end", "text": "**Diagnostic Report – Network Connectivity & OSPF Configuration**\n\n| **Component** | **Status** | **Key Findings** |\n|---------------|------------|------------------|\n| **Host‑to‑Host Pings** | Mixed | • 10/12/2‑subnet hosts can ping each other (same /24). <br>• All cross‑subnet pings (e.g., 10.1.2.0/24 ↔ 10.2.2.0/24, 10.200.0.0/24 ↔ any) return *unknown* or *ok* only for intra‑subnet traffic. |\n| **OSPF Advertisements** | Incomplete | • `switch_dist_1_1` advertises only `10.1.1.0/24` (area 1) and its /31 link. <br>• `switch_dist_2_1` advertises only `10.2.1.0/24` (area 1) and its /31 link. <br>• `router_core_1` & `router_core_2` advertise area 0 links and a few /31 links to the distribution switches, but **do not advertise the 10.1.2.0/24, 10.2.2.0/24, or 10.200.0.0/24 subnets**. <br>• `router_core_3` advertises only area 0 links. <br>• `switch_server_access` advertises `10.200.0.0/24` (area 0) and its /31 link to core 3. |\n| **Routing Impact** | Missing routes | • Because the core routers never learn the 10.1.2.0/24, 10.2.2.0/24, and 10.200.0.0/24 networks, there are no paths between those subnets. <br>• Hosts in 10.1.2.0/24 can reach each other (same LAN) but cannot reach 10.2.2.0/24 or 10.200.0.0/24. <br>• Web servers in 10.200.0.0/24 are isolated from all other subnets. |\n| **Potential Secondary Issues** | Firewall/ACLs not examined | • The *unknown* ping results could also be caused by host‑level firewalls or ACLs, but the OSPF mis‑advertisement is the primary, systemic cause. |\n\n### Root Cause Summary\nThe core routers (`router_core_1`, `router_core_2`, `router_core_3`) lack OSPF `network` statements for the following subnets:\n\n* `10.1.2.0/24` (area 1) – connected to `switch_dist_1_1`\n* `10.2.2.0/24` (area 1) – connected to `switch_dist_2_1`\n* `10.200.0.0/24` (area 0) – connected to `switch_server_access`\n\nBecause these networks are never advertised into OSPF, the core routers have no routes to them, and consequently hosts in those subnets cannot reach each other or the web‑server subnet.\n\n### Suggested Fixes\n1. **Add missing network statements** to each core router’s OSPF configuration:\n   ```bash\n   router ospf\n     network 10.1.2.0/24 area 1\n     network 10.2.2.0/24 area 1\n     network 10.200.0.0/24 area 0\n   exit\n   ```\n2. **Verify adjacency** after re‑loading the configs (check `show ip ospf neighbor` on each router).\n3. **Re‑run ping tests** between hosts in different subnets to confirm connectivity.\n4. **Optional**: If any ACLs or host firewalls are suspected, inspect them after OSPF is fixed.\n\nOnce the OSPF topology includes all subnets, the network should regain full inter‑subnet connectivity, and the ping results should change from *unknown* to *ok* for all host pairs.", "generation_info": {"model": "gpt-oss:20b", "created_at": "2025-12-16T15:06:28.42897713Z", "done": true, "done_reason": "stop", "total_duration": 38383345202, "load_duration": 75950778, "prompt_eval_count": 8005, "prompt_eval_duration": 7227458708, "eval_count": 3196, "eval_duration": 30651336253, "model_name": "gpt-oss:20b"}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 8005, "output_tokens": 3196, "total_tokens": 11201}}
